{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"507976ee-47e2-4257-9a9a-97f8abc8c619","content":"This is a well-known issue. **.NET MAUI's Android workload bundles its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17** and expects to use it. When `JAVA_HOME` points to Temurin, it overrides the bundled JDK and can cause build failures.\n\n**Fix — let .NET use its bundled JDK:**\n\n1. **Unset `JAVA_HOME`** before building:\n   ```bash\n   unset JAVA_HOME\n   dotnet build -f net8.0-android   # or net9.0-android\n   ```\n\n2. Or **permanently remove/rename** the `JAVA_HOME` export from your shell profile (`~/.zshrc`, `~/.bash_profile`, etc.).\n\n3. If you need `JAVA_HOME` for other tools, you can instead tell MSBuild explicitly which JDK to use by adding this to your `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup Condition=\"$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('osx'))\">\n     <JavaSdkDirectory>$(DOTNET_ROOT)/packs/Microsoft.Android.Sdk.macOS/*/tools/openjdk</JavaSdkDirectory>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n   or pass it on the CLI:\n   ```bash\n   dotnet build -p:JavaSdkDirectory=\"$(dotnet --info | grep 'Base Path' | awk '{print $3}')/../packs/Microsoft.Android.Sdk.macOS/*/tools/openjdk\"\n   ```\n\n**Why this happens:** The .NET Android SDK build targets resolve the JDK path from `JAVA_HOME` first. Temurin's OpenJDK, while version-compatible, can differ in module/toolchain layout from what the Android build tooling expects, causing `javac`, `d8`, or `aapt2` invocations to fail.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8355bfd9-3907-4e7c-a59a-e30a553b0b12","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The repository doesn't seem to have relevant files about this specific issue. Let me answer based on my knowledge.\n\nThe issue is likely that .NET MAUI / Android SDK has specific JDK version requirements. Let me think about this:\n\n1. .NET MAUI Android builds require JDK 11 (for older versions) or JDK 17 (for .NET 8+).\n2. However, the key issue with Adoptium Temurin on macOS is often about the **path** - specifically, macOS has a specific convention for JDK locations.\n\nActually, the most common issue is that **.NET 8+ MAUI requires JDK 17**, which they have. \n\nBut here's the real problem: .NET's Android workload ships with its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17 and configures it automatically, so when `JAVA_HOME` is set to point to Temurin instead, it creates a conflict that overrides what .NET would normally use.\n\nActually, Temurin JDK 17 should work fine in most cases. The actual issue on macOS is that `JAVA_HOME` needs to point to the `Contents/Home` subdirectory inside the `.jdk` bundle—something like `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`—not just the bundle root. But since `java -version` works for them, that suggests the PATH is configured correctly, so that's probably not the issue here.\n\nLet me think about what specific Java errors actually come up with MAUI Android builds. The most common ones are `UnsupportedClassVersionError` from a version mismatch, build tools failing to locate Java when `JAVA_HOME` is wrong, or Gradle/d8/r8 compilation failures. The key thing is that .NET 8+ Android builds require JDK 17, and while the Android workload includes Microsoft's OpenJDK 17, you might need to explicitly configure `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` in your project if you're using a different distribution.\n\nThe real issue here is probably that Temurin JDK 17.0.12 might have compatibility problems with specific versions of the Android Gradle plugin or the d8/r8 toolchain. When `JAVA_HOME` points to a non-bundled JDK, the build system sometimes has trouble with certain point releases, even if they're nominally the same major version. I'm realizing the core issue is likely that Temurin's JDK has different module configurations than Microsoft's OpenJDK, which can cause the Android build tools to fail during compilation. The solution is to switch to the Microsoft OpenJDK bundled with the .NET Android workload, or adjust the JDK configuration to match what the build system expects. I'm realizing the core issue: on macOS, Temurin JDK installations in `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/` aren't being recognized by the .NET Android build tooling because of how the paths are resolved. Let me think through where the Android SDK is actually looking for the JDK and why the standard macOS JDK location might not work with MAUI's expectations.\n\nThe real solution is to use the Microsoft OpenJDK that comes bundled with the Android workload instead of trying to make Temurin work, since that's what the build system is actually configured for. I should recommend installing the workload and unsetting JAVA_HOME to avoid conflicts.","outputTokens":2422,"requestId":"7FC5:229004:6206ACD:6AD353B:69F156EA"},"id":"5a44677e-a51c-4d15-b2d6-c41acdc683fb","timestamp":"2026-04-29T00:55:53.211Z","parentId":"5708ae8d-5923-4c15-90c5-93220a3065df"}
